<DOC><DOCNO> AP880812-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1110EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-AutoShop-Suit     08-12 0221</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Auto Shop-Suit,0226</SECOND><HEAD>Auto Shop Class Drives Student To File Lawsuit</HEAD><DATELINE>CORONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A high school student claims a teacher'sadvice in auto shop class steered him in the wrong direction, andhe's been driven to file suit over a botched clutch job.   David Price is suing the Corona-Norco Unified School Districtfor $250 in damages, claiming he received incorrect instruction onhow to replace his car's clutch last semester.   ``I was allowed to leave school in a malfunctioning car and hadto pay for a full clutch job privately,'' said Price, who was ajunior when he took the class. ``I also had to buy parts perteacher's instructions that were not necessary.''   Trial on the small claims court case is set for Aug. 29.   Price's father, Duane, said Thursday that his son triedunsuccessfully to get the school district to reimburse him for thecost of the parts and repairs. The Prices decided to sue becauseschool administrators were unresponsive, the elder Price said.   Bob Crank, the school district's assistant superintendent ofbusiness services, said he had received a copy of the lawsuitWednesday but had not had time to study it. It would be forwardedto the district's attorneys, he said.   He said he was unaware of any other complaints about the autoshop program.</TEXT></DOC>